The most interesting thing in this code is:
(top + 1) % elements.length

What does that do?
In short, this prevents the top from overflowing.
Mathematically, this line can be represented like:
top + 1 (mod elements size)

Let's put some values:
top = 49
elements size = 50

49 + 1 (mod 50) =
= 50 (mod 50) = 0

So, now the queue is circular.

Now, the implementation:

public class Queue<T> {
private static final int SIZE_QUEUE = 100;
private T[] elements;
private int top = 0, start = 0, all = 0;

@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
public Queue(int size){
    elements = (T[]) new Object[size];
}

public Queue(){
    this(SIZE_QUEUE);
}

public void add(T value){
    if (isFull()){
       throw new RuntimeException("Queue is full");
    } else {
        elements[top] = value;
        top = (top + 1) % elements.length;
        all++;
    }
}

public T remove(){
    if (isEmpty()){
        throw new RuntimeException("Queue is empty");
    } else {
        T val = elements[start];
        elements[start] = null; // Help the garbage collector
        start = (start + 1) % elements.length;
        all--;
        return val;
    }
}

public T peek(){
    if (isEmpty()){
        throw new RuntimeException("Queue is empty");
    } else {
        return elements[start];
    }
}

public boolean isFull(){
    return all == elements.length;
}

public boolean isEmpty(){
    return all == 0;
}

public int size(){
    return all;
}
}

